Laboratory Session 4 -- Arduino¶

Arduino is an open source software and hardware, which allows you to easily code around hardware, be it input hardware (e.g. sensors, buttons, potentiometers) or output hardware (e.g. LED lights, buzzers, motors).

The arduino boards are microcontrollers, circuits that integrate a central processing unit, memory and I/O, with an internal controlling BUS. These circuits are not very powerfull when compared with computers or even single board microprocessors (such as the Raspberry Pi), but they are powerfull enough for most prototyping projects and come at a relatively low cost. An original brand Arduino uno costs around 20-25, but since the hardware is open source, you can find generic-brand arduino unos at less than 5.

While there is a wide range of Arduino microntrollers, the Arduino uno is the most used board. This board features 14 digital I/O pins (6 of these can provide pulse width modulation - PWM), 6 analog input pins, and has an 8-bit CPU.

Other popular Arduino boards are the Arduino Micro, smaller, cheaper but with less pins, the Arduino Mega, large, more expensive but with many more I/O and analog pins, or the Arduino Due, exactly the same as the Arduino Mega, but with a 32-bit CPU.

For this laboratory sessions, you will be working with an Arduino Uno and a series of components.

1) Install the Arduino IDE software. Follow the recommended steps of the installation, which will install the Arduino drivers along with the software itself.

2) Open the Arduino software. We will start with the most basic example, the "Blink" example. To do this, click on File > 01.Basic > Blink. The basic code displayed will be as shown below:

In [ ]:
void setup() {
    pinMode(LED_BUILTIN, OUTPUT);
}

void loop() {
    digitalWrite(LED_BUILTIN, HIGH);
    delay(1000);
    digitalWrite(LED_BUILTIN, LOW);
    delay(1000);
}

Arduino code is a specific flavour of C++, and its basics are simple to grasp. The code basically works through a setup and a loop.

  • Setup: the setup is ran only once and is generally used to start the serial (when required) or to define whether the digital pins used are inputs or outputs. Here, you can see that the LED is defined as an output. LED_BUILTIN corresponds to a environment variable with value 13. You can see that you only ahve 12 digital I/O's; the 13th I/O is merely an integrated LED. The code simply establishes that pin 13 will be used as output.

  • Loop: the loop is a series of code that is run indefinitely. This simple example consists of turing the LED on, by writing to the previously established as output digital pin 13 the value HIGH. Then, the Arduino waits 1000ms=1s and turns the LED off. Finally, the Arduino waits 1s again, and the loop repeats indefinitely.

Insert the Arduino USB cable into your computer. You should select the board and port that you are using. To do this, go to Tools > Board and select "Arduino Uno". Then, go to Tools > Port and select the COM where your Arduino is connected. Normally, there will only be one COM for you to select, but you can always check the COM of your device on Windows' Device Manager.

After correctly choosing the board and port, click on the Upload button, the second one on the top bar. Your code will be compiled and then uploaded onto your board.

Check that the Arduino's integrated LED is indeed blinking. The LED will be found as shown on the image above. You can test different delays values to see different behaviours of the LED.

2) Multiple LEDs and push button input

For this example, start by making the connections as shown in the diagram below. Do this initially on Tinkercad Arduino Simulator. When working on more complicated projects, it is advisable to first simulate your connections. Copy the schematic of the image below to Tinkercad.

Copy the code below into Tinkercad's sketch and run the simulation.

In [ ]:
int led1 = 8;
int led2 = 9;
int led3 = 10;
int led4 = 11;
int pshbttn = 2;

void setup() {
  pinMode(led1, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(led2, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(led3, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(led4, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(pshbttn, INPUT);
}

void loop() {
  int pshVal = digitalRead(pshbttn);
    
  if (pshVal == HIGH) {
    
    digitalWrite(led1, HIGH);
    digitalWrite(led4, LOW);
    delay(25);
    digitalWrite(led2, HIGH);
    digitalWrite(led1, LOW);
    delay(25);
    digitalWrite(led3, HIGH);
    digitalWrite(led2, LOW);
    delay(25);
    digitalWrite(led4, HIGH);
    digitalWrite(led3, LOW);
    delay(25);
    
  } else {
    
    // turn LED off:
    digitalWrite(led1, LOW);
    digitalWrite(led2, LOW);
    digitalWrite(led3, LOW);
    digitalWrite(led4, LOW);
    
  }
  
}

This code shows a few new things. The first is that some variable are allocated before the setup and loop. This is simply to facilitate changing the code. For example led1 is initiated as an integer, and the port that it will be connected is the 8th. Change the ports with regards to your own connections.

The loop also features two new commands. The first is that the value of the pushbutton is read into an integer variable using the digitalRead function. The second part is C++ if clause. While different from Matlab or Python, it is easy to understand how it works.

Now, repeat the schematic with real components. Please pay attention to the resistors used. For the pushbutton, a resistor of $10 k\Omega$ should be used. For the LEDs, while a resistor of $1 k\Omega$ is shown on the diagram, an resistor between $0.1k\Omega$ and $10k\Omega$ can be used: a resistor with a large value of resistance will provide less current to the LED, making it light less bright; on the other hand using a lower value resistor will allow more current to flow, making the LED shine brighter. This comes at the cost of heating more the LED and effectively decreasing its life. You can use a resistor calculator to find the resistor's resistance from its colors. If no resistor is used, the LED would shine very brightly and quickly burn out. Do not use the LEDs without a resistor.

Your resistors will not have the same colors as the ones on the image, since they are 5 band resistor, in contrast to the 4 band ones of the image.

After setting up the hardware, start a new sketch on the Arduino IDE and copy and paste the code above. Then upload the sketch and see the results.

3) Servomotor and potentiometer

This final example introduces two new components: a servomotor and a potentiometer. A potentiometer is simply a variable resistor. If you rotate it, the resistance chanegs, and you can read the value into your arduino. On the other hand, a servomotor is a type of DC motor which has a gearbox (reducing its speed but increasing its torque) and an integrated potentiometer, meaning that it always knows the angle of its shaft. This example sets out to control the abgle of the servo's shaft by rotating the external potentiometer.

Make the connections as shown below.

As you can see, the connections are simple. There are two important details about these connections. The potentiometer should be connected to an Analog input, since the values read from it are analog (values ranging from 0 to 1023). The servo orange cable should be connected to a PWM digital port (any digital port with a "~" before the number). This is required since it is not sufficient a simple on/off port. PWM ports offer a range of values for 0 to 255 that can translate the required movement.

Start a new Arduino sketch and copy and paste the code below.

In [ ]:
#include <Servo.h>

Servo myservo;

int potpin = 0;
int val;

void setup() {
  myservo.attach(10);
  Serial.begin(9600);
}

void loop() {
  val = analogRead(potpin);
  val = map(val, 0, 1023, 0, 180);
  Serial.print(val);
  Serial.println('\r\n');
  myservo.write(val);
  delay(15);
}

The code above shows a few new functions. The first is the inclusion of the Servo library, using the code #include <Servo.h>. A servo object (named myservo) is initiated using Servo myservo;. Then, in the setup, the servo port is attached to the servo object initiated. Finally, to write values to the servo, the method .write is used with respect to the myservo object.

The servo must receive values between 0 and 180 (degrees). On the other hand, the values obtained from the potentiometer are between 0 and 1023. To convert the values, the function map is used, which receives the values that you want to map, the range of the original values, and the new desired range.

The serial is also used on this example. First, the serial is initialized in the setup. The 9600 value corresponds to the baudrate, which is simply the rate at which information is transferred in a communication channel. To write to the serial, simply use Serial.print in the loop. The Serial.println adds a new line after printing your string. For this example, the potentiometer value is printed into the serial and adding the \r\n simply sends the values to a live graph, that you will be able to see when running the example.

Note that analog inputs do not have to be alocated in the setup, in contrast to the digital ones.

Upload the sketch and open the Serial, to observe the values. First open the serial monitor, by selecting Tools > Serial Monitor, and make sure that the baud rate matches the 9600 that you established. You can see that the values are indeed being printed, but with a strange termination. That is due to the addition of \r\n required for plotting; generally, the values would simply be printed.

Now, close the serial monitor and open the serial plotter, by clicking on Tools > Serial Plotter. Again, make sure that the baud rate matches the 9600 that you established. You can graphically see the angle of the servo motor changing along time.
